data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>`, which both verifies the type and returns the cast result (MSTest v3+):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Your original direct cast `(EmailHandler)result` throws an `InvalidCastException` on failure, which produces a less informative test error. `IsInstanceOfType<T>` gives a clear assertion message **and** returns the typed value so you can keep testing properties.
